{"title_page": "Fret Fever", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Fret Fever\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Domenic Troiano]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1979\n| recorded   = 1978-1979\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock Music|Rock]], [[Soul music|Soul]], [[Pop-Rock]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]<br>(ST-11932)\n| producer   = Domenic Troiano\n| prev_title = Tricky\n| prev_year  = 1973\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''Fret Fever''''' (released under his last name of \"Troiano\") is the third solo release (and first for Capitol) by [[Italy|Italian]]/[[Canada|Canadian]] [[guitar|guitarist]]-[[singer/songwriter]] [[Domenic Troiano]] (having also done time in bands as diverse as [[James Gang]] & [[The Guess Who]]).  Self-produced and released in 1979, it featured his biggest hit in the [[disco]]-flavored \"We All Need Love\" (lead vocal-Roy Kenner).\n\n==Track listing==\n*All songs written & arranged by Domenic Troiano, except where noted.\n\n#\"[[South America|South American]] Run\" 3:41 (Troiano, [[Roy Kenner]])\n#\"Ambush\" 3:45\n#\"We All Need Love\" 3:55\n#\"It's You\" 3:14\n#\"It's Raining, It's Raining\" 3:26\n#\"Give Me a Chance\" 2:13\n#\"Your Past\" 3:44\n#\"Fret Fever\" 3:48\n#\"Brains on the Floor\" 4:01\n#\"Victim of Circumstance\" 3:38\n#\"[[Achilles]]\" 3:56\n#\"The End\" 0:45\n\n==Personnel==\n*Domenic Troiano - vocals, [[Rhythm Guitar|rhythm]], [[Lead Guitar|lead]], [[acoustic guitars]]\n*David Tyson - keyboards, additional percussion, backing vocals\n*Bob Wilson - bass, backing vocals\n*Paul DeLong - drums, percussion\n*Bob Boyer, [[Lisa Dal Bello|Dalbello]], [[Eddie Schwartz]], Fred Boyer, Colina Phillips, Shawne Jackson - backing vocals\n*Roy Kenner - Lead and background vocals\n\n==Production==\n*Produced by Domenic Troiano\n*Reissue Producer: Warren Stewart\n*Recorded & Mixed by Mike Jones, with recording assistance by Hugh Cooper\n*Mastered by [[George Marino]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.discogs.com/Troiano-Fret-Fever/release/1680350 \"Track information at Discogs]\n*[http://www.allmusic.com/album/fret-fever-mw0000545057/credits Album credits at Allmusic]\n\n[[Category:1979 albums]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Fret Fever\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Domenic Troiano]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1979\n| recorded   = 1978-1979\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock Music|Rock]], [[Soul Music|Soul]], [[Pop-Rock]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]<br>(ST-11932)\n| producer   = Domenic Troiano\n| prev_title = Tricky\n| prev_year  = 1973\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''Fret Fever''''' (released under his last name of \"Troiano\") is the third solo release (and first for Capitol) by [[Italy|Italian]]/[[Canada|Canadian]] [[guitar|guitarist]]-[[singer/songwriter]] [[Domenic Troiano]] (having also done time in bands as diverse as [[James Gang]] & [[The Guess Who]]).  Self-produced and released in 1979, it featured his biggest hit in the [[disco]]-flavored \"We All Need Love\" (lead vocal-Roy Kenner).\n\n==Track listing==\n*All songs written & arranged by Domenic Troiano, except where noted.\n\n#\"[[South America|South American]] Run\" 3:41 (Troiano, [[Roy Kenner]])\n#\"Ambush\" 3:45\n#\"We All Need Love\" 3:55\n#\"It's You\" 3:14\n#\"It's Raining, It's Raining\" 3:26\n#\"Give Me a Chance\" 2:13\n#\"Your Past\" 3:44\n#\"Fret Fever\" 3:48\n#\"Brains on the Floor\" 4:01\n#\"Victim of Circumstance\" 3:38\n#\"[[Achilles]]\" 3:56\n#\"The End\" 0:45\n\n==Personnel==\n*Domenic Troiano - vocals, [[Rhythm Guitar|rhythm]], [[Lead Guitar|lead]], [[acoustic guitars]]\n*David Tyson - keyboards, additional percussion, backing vocals\n*Bob Wilson - bass, backing vocals\n*Paul DeLong - drums, percussion\n*Bob Boyer, [[Lisa Dal Bello|Dalbello]], [[Eddie Schwartz]], Fred Boyer, Colina Phillips, Shawne Jackson - backing vocals\n*Roy Kenner - Lead and background vocals\n\n==Production==\n*Produced by Domenic Troiano\n*Reissue Producer: Warren Stewart\n*Recorded & Mixed by Mike Jones, with recording assistance by Hugh Cooper\n*Mastered by [[George Marino]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.discogs.com/Troiano-Fret-Fever/release/1680350 \"Track information at Discogs]\n*[http://www.allmusic.com/album/fret-fever-mw0000545057/credits Album credits at Allmusic]\n\n[[Category:1979 albums]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSoul music (disambiguation)(link changed toSoul music) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fret_Fever"}
{"title_page": "Hi-Five (album)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Hi-Five\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Hi-Five]]\n| cover      = Hifivealbum.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 25, 1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Hi-Five/dp/B0000004W6|title=Hi-Five|date=25 September 1990|publisher=|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n| recorded   = November 1989\u2013May 1990\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[R&B]], [[new jack swing]]\n| length     = 51:39\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| producer   = [[Teddy Riley]], [[Bernard Belle]], [[Eric Foster White]], Dave Way, Alvin Moody, Vincent Bell, Carl Bourelly, Kevin Johnson, Frankie Smith, William Walton\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Keep It Goin' On]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Hi-Five\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = I Just Can't Handle It\n | single1date = November 7, 1990\n | single2     = [[I Like the Way (The Kissing Game)]]\n | single2date = January 2, 1991\n | single3     = [[I Can't Wait Another Minute]]\n | single3date = June 1, 1991\n | single4     = Just Another Girlfriend\n | single4date = July 16, 1991\n | single5     = Just Another Girlfriend (Remix)\n | single5date = October 1991\n}}\n}}\n'''''Hi-Five''''' is the debut album by the American R&B vocal group [[Hi-Five]]. Released on September 25, 1990, The album peaked at number thirty eight on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart. Driven by the hit [[single (music)|singles]] \"I Just Can't Handle It\" (R&B #10), \"[[I Like the Way (The Kissing Game)]]\" (#1 R&B/Pop), \"[[I Can't Wait Another Minute]]\" (R&B #1, Pop #8) and \"Just Another Girlfriend\" (R&B #41), the album received an [[RIAA]] [[platinum record|platinum]] certification. Also, ''Hi-Five'' is the only album to feature original Hi-Five member Toriano Easley, who was later arrested for both [[first-degree murder]] (after a confrontation with an [[acquaintance]]) and [[manslaughter]]. Also, Easley had previously marked his both only single cover and [[music video]] appearances from the debut [[album]] with the group, \"I Just Can't Handle It\" before his expulsion from the group. Toriano is the co-lead singer on \"The Way You Said Goodbye,\" \"Rag Doll,\" \"I Can't Wait Another Minute,\" and \"I Know Love.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soulculture.com/music/we-werent-thinking-about-the-money-marcus-sanders-revisits-hi-fives-debut-album-return-to-the-classics/|title=Marcus Sanders revisits Hi-Five's debut album - Return To The Classics - SoulCulture|publisher=}}</ref> In the video for \"I Can't Wait Another Minute\", Treston Irby (who is Easley's replacement) lip syncs Toriano's lead vocals (none of the songs were re-recorded with Treston).\n\n==Background==\nThe song, \"Too Young\" (in a single edit version), also appeared on the [[Boyz n the Hood (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 1991 [[John Singleton]] film ''[[Boyz n the Hood]].'' It is the first recorded appearance of [[Mobb Deep]] rapper [[Prodigy (rapper)|Prodigy]] who was 15 when this song was released, which he revealed in his book ''My Infamous Life: The Autobiography of Mobb Deep's Prodigy''.<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=My Infamous Life: The Autobiography of Mobb Deep's Prodigy|author1=Johnson, A.|author2=Checkoway, L.|date=2012|publisher=Touchstone|isbn=9781439103197|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NNnZAMnSfV4C&pg=PA36|page=36|accessdate=2015-06-24}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1          = I Just Can't Handle It\n| writer1         = Bernard Bell, Teddy Riley\n| extra1          = Bell, Riley\n| length1         = 4:32\n| title2          = Just Another Girlfriend\n| writer2         = Eric Foster White\n| extra2          = White\n| length2         = 4:01\n| title3          = [[I Like the Way (The Kissing Game)]]\n| writer3         = Riley, Bell, [[Dave Way]]\n| extra3          = Riley, Bell, Way\n| length3         = 5:49\n| title4          = Rag Doll\n| writer4         = Alvin Moody\n| extra4          = Moody\n| length4         = 4:39\n| title5          = [[I Can't Wait Another Minute]]\n| writer5         = White\n| extra5          = White\n| length5         = 5:03\n| title6          = Too Young\n| writer6         = Carl & Jean-Paul Bourelly, Roz Davis\n| extra6          = Carl & Jean-Paul Bourelly\n| length6         = 5:13\n| title7          = Merry-Go-Round\n| writer7         = Carl Bourelly, Kevin Johnson, Sean Richards  \n| extra7          = C. Bourelly, Kevin Johnson\n| length7         = 5:11\n| title8          = The Way You Said Goodbye\n| writer8         = White\n| extra8          = White\n| length8         = 4:41\n| title9          = Sweetheart\n| writer9         = Bourelly, Bourelly, Richards, Davis,\n| extra9          = C. Bourelly\n| length9         = 4:09\n| title10         = I Know Love\n| writer10        = William Walton\n| extra10         = Watson, Frankie Smith\n| length10        = 3:54\n| title11         = Just Another Girlfriend (Remix)\n| writer11        = White\n| extra11         = White\n| length11        = 4:07\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Hi-Five===\n*Tony Thompson \u2013 harmony and backing vocals\n*Roderick Clark \u2013 harmony and backing vocals\n*Marcus Sanders \u2013 harmony and backing vocals\n*Toriano Easley \u2013 harmony and backing vocals\n*Russell Neal \u2013 harmony and backing vocals\n\n'''Additional singers'''\n*Bernard Bell \u2013 backing vocals\n*Tim Cashion \u2013 backing vocals\n*Roiz Davis \u2013 backing vocals\n*Gordon Dukes \u2013 backing vocals\n*LaGaylia Frazier \u2013 backing vocals\n*Frederick Gordon \u2013 backing vocals\n*[[Dave Hollister]] \u2013 backing vocals\n*John James \u2013 backing vocals\n*Alvin Moody \u2013 backing vocals\n*Teddy Riley \u2013 backing vocals\n*Sean LaBreeze \u2013 backing vocals\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Musicians===\n*Carl Bourelly \u2013 keyboards, drum programming\n*William Walton \u2013 keyboards, drum programming\n*Jean-Paul Bourelly \u2013 guitars, keyboards\n*Fritz Cadet \u2013 guitar\n*Josh Grau \u2013 guitar\n*Frankie Smith \u2013 guitar\n*Vincent Henry \u2013 harmonica, saxophone\n*Kevin Johnson \u2013 keyboards, drums, percussion\n*Sean Richards \u2013 drum programming\n*[[Eric Foster White]] \u2013 keyboards, drum programming, trombone\n*[[DeVante Swing]] \u2013 mixing\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000316079|title=''Hi-Five''}}\n*[http://www.discogs.com/Hi-Five-Hi-Five/release/754240 Production information at discogs]\n{{Hi-Five}}\n[[Category:1990 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Hi-Five albums]]\n[[Category:Jive Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Teddy Riley]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Hi-Five\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Hi-Five]]\n| cover      = Hifivealbum.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 25, 1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Hi-Five/dp/B0000004W6|title=Hi-Five|date=25 September 1990|publisher=|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n| recorded   = November 1989\u2013May 1990\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]], [[Soul Music|soul]], [[R&B]], [[new jack swing]]\n| length     = 51:39\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| producer   = [[Teddy Riley]], [[Bernard Belle]], [[Eric Foster White]], Dave Way, Alvin Moody, Vincent Bell, Carl Bourelly, Kevin Johnson, Frankie Smith, William Walton\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Keep It Goin' On]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Hi-Five\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = I Just Can't Handle It\n | single1date = November 7, 1990\n | single2     = [[I Like the Way (The Kissing Game)]]\n | single2date = January 2, 1991\n | single3     = [[I Can't Wait Another Minute]]\n | single3date = June 1, 1991\n | single4     = Just Another Girlfriend\n | single4date = July 16, 1991\n | single5     = Just Another Girlfriend (Remix)\n | single5date = October 1991\n}}\n}}\n'''''Hi-Five''''' is the debut album by the American R&B vocal group [[Hi-Five]]. Released on September 25, 1990, The album peaked at number thirty eight on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart. Driven by the hit [[single (music)|singles]] \"I Just Can't Handle It\" (R&B #10), \"[[I Like the Way (The Kissing Game)]]\" (#1 R&B/Pop), \"[[I Can't Wait Another Minute]]\" (R&B #1, Pop #8) and \"Just Another Girlfriend\" (R&B #41), the album received an [[RIAA]] [[platinum record|platinum]] certification. Also, ''Hi-Five'' is the only album to feature original Hi-Five member Toriano Easley, who was later arrested for both [[first-degree murder]] (after a confrontation with an [[acquaintance]]) and [[manslaughter]]. Also, Easley had previously marked his both only single cover and [[music video]] appearances from the debut [[album]] with the group, \"I Just Can't Handle It\" before his expulsion from the group. Toriano is the co-lead singer on \"The Way You Said Goodbye,\" \"Rag Doll,\" \"I Can't Wait Another Minute,\" and \"I Know Love.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soulculture.com/music/we-werent-thinking-about-the-money-marcus-sanders-revisits-hi-fives-debut-album-return-to-the-classics/|title=Marcus Sanders revisits Hi-Five's debut album - Return To The Classics - SoulCulture|publisher=}}</ref> In the video for \"I Can't Wait Another Minute\", Treston Irby (who is Easley's replacement) lip syncs Toriano's lead vocals (none of the songs were re-recorded with Treston).\n\n==Background==\nThe song, \"Too Young\" (in a single edit version), also appeared on the [[Boyz n the Hood (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 1991 [[John Singleton]] film ''[[Boyz n the Hood]].'' It is the first recorded appearance of [[Mobb Deep]] rapper [[Prodigy (rapper)|Prodigy]] who was 15 when this song was released, which he revealed in his book ''My Infamous Life: The Autobiography of Mobb Deep's Prodigy''.<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=My Infamous Life: The Autobiography of Mobb Deep's Prodigy|author1=Johnson, A.|author2=Checkoway, L.|date=2012|publisher=Touchstone|isbn=9781439103197|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NNnZAMnSfV4C&pg=PA36|page=36|accessdate=2015-06-24}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1          = I Just Can't Handle It\n| writer1         = Bernard Bell, Teddy Riley\n| extra1          = Bell, Riley\n| length1         = 4:32\n| title2          = Just Another Girlfriend\n| writer2         = Eric Foster White\n| extra2          = White\n| length2         = 4:01\n| title3          = [[I Like the Way (The Kissing Game)]]\n| writer3         = Riley, Bell, [[Dave Way]]\n| extra3          = Riley, Bell, Way\n| length3         = 5:49\n| title4          = Rag Doll\n| writer4         = Alvin Moody\n| extra4          = Moody\n| length4         = 4:39\n| title5          = [[I Can't Wait Another Minute]]\n| writer5         = White\n| extra5          = White\n| length5         = 5:03\n| title6          = Too Young\n| writer6         = Carl & Jean-Paul Bourelly, Roz Davis\n| extra6          = Carl & Jean-Paul Bourelly\n| length6         = 5:13\n| title7          = Merry-Go-Round\n| writer7         = Carl Bourelly, Kevin Johnson, Sean Richards  \n| extra7          = C. Bourelly, Kevin Johnson\n| length7         = 5:11\n| title8          = The Way You Said Goodbye\n| writer8         = White\n| extra8          = White\n| length8         = 4:41\n| title9          = Sweetheart\n| writer9         = Bourelly, Bourelly, Richards, Davis,\n| extra9          = C. Bourelly\n| length9         = 4:09\n| title10         = I Know Love\n| writer10        = William Walton\n| extra10         = Watson, Frankie Smith\n| length10        = 3:54\n| title11         = Just Another Girlfriend (Remix)\n| writer11        = White\n| extra11 