{"title_page": "K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish golfer}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund\n| image             = \n| imagesize         = <!-- Optional, default is 200px -->\n| caption           = \n| fullname          = K\u00e4rstin Helena Ehrnlund Strand \t\n| nickname          = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1959|2|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Karlstad]], [[Sweden]]\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1959|2|10|df=y}} -->\n| death_place       = \n| height            = \n| weight            = \n| nationality       = {{SWE}}\n| residence         = Ytterby, [[Kung\u00e4lv]], [[Sweden]]\n| spouse            = Erik Strand (1985-) \n| partner           = \n| children          = 2 \n| college           = \n| yearpro           = 1979\n| retired           = 1985 \n| tour              = \n| extour            = [[Ladies European Tour]]\n| prowins           = 2\n| letwins           = 2\n| otherwins         = \n| majorwins         = <!-- Number of Major Championship wins -->\n| nabisco           = \n| lpga              = \n| wusopen           = \n| wbritopen         = \n| evian             = \n| wghofid           = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame member ID -->\n| wghofyear         = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame year inducted -->\n| award1            = <!-- Achievement or award details -->\n| year1             = <!-- Year(s) of achievement or award -->\n| award2            = \n| year2             = \n| awardssection     = <!-- location of awards page or section -->\n}}\n'''K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund''' (born 10 February 1959 in [[Karlstad]]) is a [[List of Swedish professional golfers|Swedish professional golfer]]. She was the first Swedish woman to join a [[professional golf tours|professional golf tour]] and the first Swede to record a victory on an international tour.\n\n==Early years==\nEhrnlund's father Sven-Erik was a well-known coach for the local [[bandy]] team, Surte Bandy Club, in the 1970s, playing at the highest level in [[Sweden]]. Living in the small society Bohus, Sweden, the family started playing golf at nearby Lyseg\u00e5rden Golf Club, but soon switched to Gullbringa Golf & Country Club, the same club as were, future [[LPGA Tour]] winners, [[Helen Alfredsson]] and [[Carin Koch]] started their careers a few years later. Ehrnlund found more interest in horse riding at young ages, but allergy against horses forced her to golf instead. It was later found that her allergy was against hay. At 15 years of age, she moved to [[Palm Springs, California]], for six months to practice for [[Johnny Revolta]] during the Swedish winter and she came back for the same period the next year.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gp.se/sport/golfprofilen-k%C3%A4rstin-ehrnlund-strand-visade-v%C3%A4gen-f%C3%B6r-alla-kvinnor-1.5114745 |title=Golfprofilen K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund Strand visade v\u00e4gen f\u00f6r alla kvinnor |newspaper=G\u00f6teborgs-Posten |location=Gothenburg, Sweden |date=January 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nIn 1976, Ehrnlund sensationally reached the final of the Swedish Match-play Championship, losing to [[Liv Wollin]], who won the tournament for the ninth time.\n\nStill at junior age, Ehrnlund dominated Swedish amateur golf, winning the [[SM Match Play|Swedish Match-play Championship]] in 1977 and 1978, as well as the open amateur championships of Sweden, Germany and Austria in 1978. At the end of  the 1978 season and her amateur career, she represented Sweden, together with [[Liv Wollin]] and Charlotte Mongomery, at the [[Espirito Santo Trophy]] in Pacific Harbour, [[Fiji]], were the Swedish team finished 8th.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1979, Ehrnlund turned professional on the nascent Women's Professional Golf Association (WPGA) Tour, later renamed [[Ladies European Tour]]. With small prize amounts available, she had to rely on sponsor support and usually travelled by car between tournaments, living in a caravan and sometimes with her father as driver and caddie.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn August 1980 Ehrnlund played the Welsh Classic at [[Whitchurch Golf Club]] in [[Cardiff]], Wales. She was in the lead after two rounds with 68\u201374, and when the last round was cancelled due to rain, she was declared the winner. Four years later she won her second Ladies European Tour title, the United Friendly Tournament at two-time [[Ryder Cup]]-venue [[Southport and Ainsdale Golf Club]] near [[Liverpool]], [[England]].<ref name=\":2\">[http://svenskagolfmuseet.se/golfens-profiler/ Golf Profiles], Swedish Golf Museum, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref>\n\nAt the 1981 Volvo International, the second edition of the first Swedish LET Tournament, at Albatross Golf Club in Gothenburg, Ehrnlund finished second after Bevelry Lewis, England. In 1983, Ehrnlund reached a career best finish of 7th on the Ladies European Tour Order-of-Merit ranking.\n\nSix years after Ehrnlunds first victory on the ladies tour, [[Ove Sellberg]] became the first Swede to record a victory on the [[European Tour]] in 1986. At this time, Ehrnlund had just retired from competitive golf. Ehrnlund is regarded as an important pioneer in women's professional golf in Sweden and a model for later coming generations, making their successes possible. At the opening of the Swedish Golf Museum in June 2000, she was one of ten players, among names as [[Annika S\u00f6renstam]] and [[Jesper Parnevik]], presented as important in the history of Swedish golf.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nSince 1991, Ehrnlund and her husband Erik, also a golf professional, runs their own 9-hole golf course, Bollestad Golf Club, between [[Marstrand]] and Kung\u00e4lv, Sweden, but none of their two children, Victor and Amanda, became golf professionals.<ref name=\":1\" /> Until 2019, Ehrnlund also ran a shop at [[G\u00f6teborg Landvetter Airport]]. Since her retirement after the 1985 season she did not play an 18-hole round of golf for 13 years and then waited another 21 years.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Amateur wins==\n*1977 [[SM Match Play|Swedish Match-play Championship]]\n*1978 Swedish Junior Stroke-play Championship, [[SM Match Play|Swedish Match-play Championship]], Swedish International Stroke-play Championship, German Open Amateur Championship, Austrian Open Amateur Championship\n\nSources:<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.expressen.se/gt/sport/golf/pionjaren-som-domdes-ut-bodde-i-husvagn-/ |title=Pionj\u00e4ren som d\u00f6mdes ut - bodde i husvagn |newspaper=Expressen |location=Stockholm, Sweden |date=April 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>[http://www.svenskgolf.se/artiklar/folja/20120816/har-ar-alla-vinnare-i-sm-match SM Match Winners], Swedish Golf, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref>\n\n==Professional wins (2)==\n===Ladies European Tour (2)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!No.\n!Date\n!Tournament\n!Winning score\n!Margin of<br>victory\n!Runner(s)-up\n|-\n|1\n|28 Aug 1980\n|McEwans Lager Welsh Classic\n|\u22122 (68-74=142)*\n|2 strokes\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} Jane Chapman\n|-\n|2\n|5 Aug 1984\n|United Friendly Tournament\n|\u22124 (75-72-72-69=288)\n|4 strokes\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} Jane Forrest {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Dale Reid]]\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>'' Note: The 1980 McEwans Lager Welsh Classic was shortened from 54 to 36 holes due to rain.''<br>Source:<ref>[http://www.golf.se/globalassets/tavling/blagula-segrar/alla-svenska-segrar.pdf Swedish Professional Tour Victories], Swedish Golf Association, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.e-magin.se/paper/7m49qpt6/popup/1? |title=K\u00e4rstin skrev golfhistoria |trans-title=K\u00e4rstin wrote history |magazine=Svensk Golf |date=July 1980 |page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.e-magin.se/paper/dv6ftvf8/popup/1? |title=K\u00e4rstin - \u00c4ntligen fick hon en 72-h\u00e5lsseger |trans-title=K\u00e4rstin - Finally she got a 72-hole victory |magazine=Svensk Golf |date=September 1984 |page=7, 64}}</ref>\n\n==Team appearances==\n'''Amateur'''\n*[[Espirito Santo Trophy]] (representing Sweden): 1978<ref name=\":0\">{{citeweb |url=http://www.e-magin.se/paper/1pfc350j/popup/1? |title=Golf - Den Stora Sporten' |language=Swedish |trans-title=Golf - the Great Sport |publisher=Swedish Golf Federation 100 Years |pages=184, 209, 220, 221}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Golfdata|11175}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ehrnlund, Karstin}}\n[[Category:Swedish female golfers]]\n[[Category:Ladies European Tour golfers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Karlstad]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gothenburg]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swedish golfer}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund\n| image             = \n| imagesize         = <!-- Optional, default is 200px -->\n| caption           = \n| fullname          = K\u00e4rstin Helena Ehrnlund Strand \t\n| nickname          = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1959|2|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Karlstad]], [[Sweden]]\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1959|2|10|df=y}} -->\n| death_place       = \n| height            = \n| weight            = \n| nationality       = {{SWE}}\n| residence         = Ytterby, [[Kung\u00e4lv]], [[Sweden]]\n| spouse            = Erik Strand (1985-) \n| partner           = \n| children          = 2 \n| college           = \n| yearpro           = 1979\n| retired           = 1985 \n| tour              = \n| extour            = [[Ladies European Tour]]\n| prowins           = 2\n| letwins           = 2\n| otherwins         = \n| majorwins         = <!-- Number of Major Championship wins -->\n| nabisco           = \n| lpga              = \n| wusopen           = \n| wbritopen         = \n| evian             = \n| wghofid           = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame member ID -->\n| wghofyear         = <!-- World Golf Hall of Fame year inducted -->\n| award1            = <!-- Achievement or award details -->\n| year1             = <!-- Year(s) of achievement or award -->\n| award2            = \n| year2             = \n| awardssection     = <!-- location of awards page or section -->\n}}\n'''K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund''' (born 10 February 1959 in [[Karlstad]]) is a [[List of Swedish professional golfers|Swedish professional golfer]]. She was the first Swedish woman to join a [[professional golf tours|professional golf tour]] and the first Swede to record a victory on an international tour.\n\n==Early years==\nEhrnlund's father Sven-Erik was a well-known coach for the local [[bandy]] team, Surte Bandy Club, in the 1970s, playing at the highest level in [[Sweden]]. Living in the small society Bohus, Sweden, the family started playing golf at nearby Lyseg\u00e5rden Golf Club, but soon switched to Gullbringa Golf & Country Club, the same club as were, future [[LPGA Tour]] winners, [[Helen Alfredsson]] and [[Carin Koch]] started their careers a few years later. Ehrnlund found more interest in horse riding at young ages, but allergy against horses forced her to golf instead. It was later found that her allergy was against hay. At 15 years of age, she moved to [[Palm Springs, California]], for six months to practice for [[Johnny Revolta]] during the Swedish winter and she came back for the same period the next year.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gp.se/sport/golfprofilen-k%C3%A4rstin-ehrnlund-strand-visade-v%C3%A4gen-f%C3%B6r-alla-kvinnor-1.5114745 |title=Golfprofilen K\u00e4rstin Ehrnlund Strand visade v\u00e4gen f\u00f6r alla kvinnor |newspaper=G\u00f6teborgs-Posten |location=Gothenburg, Sweden |date=January 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nIn 1976, Ehrnlund sensationally reached the final of the Swedish Match-play Championship, losing to Liv Wollin, who won the tournament for the ninth time.\n\nStill at junior age, Ehrnlund dominated Swedish amateur golf, winning the [[SM Match Play|Swedish Match-play Championship]] in 1977 and 1978, as well as the open amateur championships of Sweden, Germany and Austria in 1978. At the end of  the 1978 season and her amateur career, she represented Sweden, together with [[Liv Wollin]] and Charlotte Mongomery, at the [[Espirito Santo Trophy]] in Pacific Harbour, [[Fiji]], were the Swedish team finished 8th.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1979, Ehrnlund turned professional on the nascent Women's Professional Golf Association (WPGA) Tour, later renamed [[Ladies European Tour]]. With small prize amounts available, she had to rely on sponsor support and usually travelled by car between tournaments, living in a caravan and sometimes with her father as driver and caddie.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn August 1980 Ehrnlund played the Welsh Classic at [[Whitchurch Golf Club]] in [[Cardiff]], Wales. She was in the lead after two rounds with 68\u201374, and when the last round was cancelled due to rain, she was declared the winner. Four years later she won her second Ladies European Tour title, the United Friendly Tournament at two-time [[Ryder Cup]]-venue [[Southport and Ainsdale Golf Club]] near [[Liverpool]], [[England]].<ref name=\":2\">[http://svenskagolfmuseet.se/golfens-profiler/ Golf Profiles], Swedish Golf Museum, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref>\n\nAt the 1981 Volvo International, the second edition of the first Swedish LET Tournament, at Albatross Golf Club in Gothenburg, Ehrnlund finished second after Bevelry Lewis, England. In 1983, Ehrnlund reached a career best finish of 7th on the Ladies European Tour Order-of-Merit ranking.\n\nSix years after Ehrnlunds first victory on the ladies tour, [[Ove Sellberg]] became the first Swede to record a victory on the [[European Tour]] in 1986. At this time, Ehrnlund had just retired from competitive golf. Ehrnlund is regarded as an important pioneer in women's professional golf in Sweden and a model for later coming generations, making their successes possible. At the opening of the Swedish Golf Museum in June 2000, she was one of ten players, among names as [[Annika S\u00f6renstam]] and [[Jesper Parnevik]], presented as important in the history of Swedish golf.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nSince 1991, Ehrnlund and her husband Erik, also a golf professional, runs their own 9-hole golf course, Bollestad Golf Club, between [[Marstrand]] and Kung\u00e4lv, Sweden, but none of their two children, Victor and Amanda, became golf professionals.<ref name=\":1\" /> Until 2019, Ehrnlund also ran a shop at [[G\u00f6teborg Landvetter Airport]]. Since her retirement after the 1985 season she did not play an 18-hole round of golf for 13 years and then waited another 21 years.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Amateur wins==\n*1977 [[SM Match Play|Swedish Match-play Championship]]\n*1978 Swedish Junior Stroke-play Championship, [[SM Match Play|Swedish Match-play Championship]], Swedish International Stroke-play Championship, German Open Amateur Championship, Austrian Open Amateur Championship\n\nSources:<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.expressen.se/gt/sport/golf/pionjaren-som-domdes-ut-bodde-i-husvagn-/ |title=Pionj\u00e4ren som d\u00f6mdes ut - bodde i husvagn |newspaper=Expressen |location=Stockholm, Sweden |date=April 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>[http://www.svenskgolf.se/artiklar/folja/20120816/har-ar-alla-vinnare-i-sm-match SM Match Winners], Swedish Golf, accessed 17 November 2016 {{in lang|sv}}</ref>\n\n==Professional wins (2)==\n===Ladies European Tour (2)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!No.\n!Date\n!Tournament\n!Winning score\n!Margin of<br>victory\n!Runner(s)-up\n|-\n|1\n|28 Aug 1980\n|McEwans Lager Welsh Classic\n|\u22122 (68-74=142)*\n|2 strokes\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} Jane Chapman\n|-\n|2\n|5 Aug 1984\n|United Friendly Tournament\n|\u22124 (75-72-72-69=288)\n|4 strokes\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} Jane Forrest {{