{"title_page": "\u00c9ric Woerth", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Expand French|topic=gov|date=February 2017}}\n{{ infobox Politician\n| name           = \u00c9ric Woerth\n| image          = \u00c9ric Woerth 2.jpg\n| office         = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br>for [[Oise's 4th constituency]]\n| term_start     = 17 June 2012\n| term_end       =\n| predecessor    = [[Christian Patria]]\n| office2        = [[Mayor (France)|Mayor]] of [[Chantilly, Oise|Chantilly]]\n| term_start2    = 1995\n| term_end2      = 2017\n| predecessor2   = Philippe Courboin\n| successor2     = Isabelle Wojtowiez\n| office3        = [[List of Budget Ministers of France|Minister of Budget]]\n| term_start3    = 2007\n| term_end3      = 2010\n| president3     = [[Nicolas Sarkozy]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]]\n| predecessor3   = [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Cop\u00e9]]\n| successor3     = [[Fran\u00e7ois Baroin]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1956|01|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Creil]], [[France]]\n| nationality    = [[France|French]]\n| party          = [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]]\n| alma_mater     = [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]], [[Sciences Po]], [[HEC Paris]]\n| spouse         = Florence Henry\n| children       = 2\n}}\n'''\u00c9ric Woerth''' (born 29 January 1956) is a French politician of [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] (LR).\n\n==Early life and education==\nWoerth was born in [[Creil]], [[Oise]]. He studied at [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]], [[HEC School of Management]] and [[Institut d'\u00c9tudes Politiques de Paris]]. \n\n==Political career==\n===Career in local politics===\n'''''Municipal Council'''''\n\nMayor of [[Chantilly, Oise]] : 1995-2004 (Resignation) / And since 2005. Reelected in 2001, 2005, 2008.\n\nDeputy-mayor of [[Chantilly, Oise]] : 2004-2005.\n\nMunicipal councillor of [[Chantilly, Oise]] : Since 1995. Reelected in 2001, 2008.\n\n'''''Community of communes Council'''''\n\nPresident of the [[Communaut\u00e9 de communes]] of the aire cantilenne{{typo help inline|reason=similar to cantilene|date=November 2019}} : Since 1995. Reelected in 2001, 2008.\n\nMember of the [[Communaut\u00e9 de communes]] of the aire cantilienne : Since 1995. Reelected in 2001, 2008.\n\nVice-president of the Regional Council of Picardy : 1992-1998.\n\nRegional councillor of [[Picardy]] : 1986-2002 (Resignation). Reelected in 1992, 1998.\n\n===Member of the National Assembly, 2002\u20132004===\nWoerth was elected [[National Assembly of France|''d\u00e9put\u00e9'']] for [[Oise]] in 2002. In parliament, he served on the Finance Committee from 2002 until 2004.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA2960 \u00c9ric Woerth] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref> \n\nIn addition to his parliamentary work, Woerth was the treasurer of the [[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] until he resigned in July 2010.<ref>[http://www.france-info.com/france-politique-2010-07-13-eric-woerth-va-bien-sur-quitter-son-poste-de-tresorier-de-l-ump-465443-9-10.html ''Eric Woerth va, \"bien s\u00fbr\", quitter son poste de tr\u00e9sorier de l\u2019UMP''] (Eric Worth will \u201cof course\u201d resign his post as treasurer of UMP)</ref>\n\n===Career in government===\nWoerth was state secretary for state reform in the government<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/may/13/france.worlddispatch|title=Commission impossible|last=Henley|first=Jon|date=2004-05-13|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=2017-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> of [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Jean-Pierre Raffarin]] from 2004 to 2005.\n\nWoerth founded the \"''club de la boussole''\", a group of UMP ''d\u00e9put\u00e9s'', and is a member of the ''[[R\u00e9formateurs]]'', a liberal trend within the UMP.\n\nWoerth was the Minister for the Budget, Public Accounts and the Civil Service from 2007 until 2010, in the government of [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]].<ref>[http://www.elysee.fr/elysee/elysee.fr/francais/interventions/2007/mai/composition_du_gouvernement.77059.html Communiqu\u00e9 de la Pr\u00e9sidence de la R\u00e9publique concernant la composition du gouvernement de M. Fran\u00e7ois FILLON, Premier ministre. ], ''[[\u00c9lys\u00e9e Palace]], 18 May 2007.</ref> In this capacity, he oversaw French authorities obtaining Swiss bank account data amid a push to catch tax cheats.<ref>David Jolly (August 30, 2009), [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/31/business/global/31iht-tax.html France Pursues Tax Cheats Using Swiss Banks] ''[[International Herald Tribune]]''.</ref>\n\nWoerth later served as [[Minister of Labour (France)|Minister of Labor, Solidarity and Civil Service]] from March until November 2010.<ref>http://www.foxbusiness.com/story/markets/frances-woerth-named-labor-minister-budget-minister/</ref>\n\n===Member of the National Assembly, 2010\u2013present===\nIn parliament, Woerth served on the Committee on Foreign Affairs from 2010 until 2012 before moving to the Finance Committee in 2012.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA2960 \u00c9ric Woerth] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref> In addition to his committee assignments, he has been a member of the [[Franco-German Parliamentary Assembly]] since 2019.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA2960 \u00c9ric Woerth] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref>\n\nIn the Republicans\u2019 [[2016 The Republicans (France) presidential primary|2016 presidential primaries]], Woerth endorsed [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]] as the party's candidate for the office of [[President of France]].<ref>[https://www.lopinion.fr/video/actu/eric-woerth-francois-fillon-sera-tres-grand-president-republique-115224 \u00c9ric Woerth : \u00abFran\u00e7ois Fillon sera un tr\u00e8s grand pr\u00e9sident de la R\u00e9publique\u00bb] ''[[L'Opinion]]'', November 25, 2016.</ref> In the Republicans\u2019 [[2017 The Republicans (France) leadership election|2017 leadership election]], he endorsed [[Laurent Wauquiez]].<ref>Ludovic Vigogne (October 11, 2017), [https://www.lopinion.fr/edition/politique/liste-136-parrains-laurent-wauquiez-135723 La liste des 136 parrains de Laurent Wauquiez] ''[[L'Opinion (French newspaper)|L'Opinion]]''.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Woerth was one of the few LR members who abstained from a vote on the French ratification of the [[European Union]]\u2019s [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA) with [[Canada]].<ref>Maxime Vaudano (24 July 2019), [https://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2019/07/24/ceta-qui-a-vote-quoi-parmi-les-deputes_5493039_4355770.html CETA : qui a vot\u00e9 quoi parmi les d\u00e9put\u00e9s] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref>\n\nTogether with [[Benjamin Dirx]], Woerth published a non-legally binding report in 2019 which garnered international attention for its recommendations on preventing [[Short (finance)|short-sellers]] and activists from unfairly destabilising French corporates. These included widening the disclosures of short positions to [[Derivative (finance)|derivatives instruments]], pushing for more transparency around the borrowing and lending of stock, and investigating whether market functions are jeopardised once short selling reaches a certain volume of shares.<ref>David Keohane and Harriet Agnew (October 2, 2019), [https://www.ft.com/content/1a8fbed2-e4fe-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59 France seeks crackdown on short sellers and activist investors] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref><ref>Laurence Boisseau (December 3, 2019), [https://www.lesechos.fr/finance-marches/marches-financiers/lactiviste-muddy-waters-defend-les-vertus-de-la-vente-a-decouvert-1153121 L'activiste Muddy Waters d\u00e9fend les vertus de la vente \u00e0 d\u00e9couvert] ''[[Les \u00c9chos (France)|Les \u00c9chos]]''.</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nOn 5 July 2010, following its investigations on the ''Liliane Bettencourt and \u00c9ric Woerth'' political controversy, the online newspaper [[Mediapart]] revealed a report where Claire Thibout, an ex-accountant working for [[Liliane Bettencourt]], accused Nicolas Sarkozy and Woerth of receiving illegal campaign donations in 2007, in cash.<ref>[http://www.mediapart.fr/ ''L'ex-comptable des Bettencourt accuse: des enveloppes d'argent \u00e0 Woerth et \u00e0 Sarkozy''], original report, in French<!-- right now on the main page, no other URL --></ref><ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/e72598de-88d5-11df-8925-00144feab49a.html Financial Times]</ref> The ''[[Canard encha\u00een\u00e9]]'' and ''[[Marianne (magazine)|Marianne]]'' weeklies later revealed that Woerth authorized the sale of the [[Compiegne]] racetrack to a group with close connections to the [[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]], for a very low price and through an improper procedure.<ref>[http://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Actualite/Compiegne-Woerth-reste-en-selle-207418/ \u00ab Compi\u00e8gne : Woerth reste en selle \u00bb], ''[[Le Journal du dimanche]]'', 14 juillet 2010.</ref> He was placed under formal investigation by the [[Cour de Justice de la R\u00e9publique]] for that sale. All charges against him were dismissed in 2015.<ref>[[:fr:Affaire Woerth-Bettencourt#D\u00e9cision de renvois en correctionnelle et relaxe]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.blog-ewoerth.com/ \u00c9ric Woerth's blog] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2010/07/02/affaire-bettencourt-les-banques-suisses-chargent-eric-woerth_1381985_3224.html#ens_id=1373579&xtor=RSS-3208 Affaire Bettencourt : les banques suisses chargent Eric Woerth], ''Le Monde'' (2 July 2010) {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.liberation.fr/societe/01012302681-la-justice-rattrape-woerth-au-pas-de-course# la justice rattrape woerth au pas de course], ''Lib\u00e9ration'' (17 November 2010) {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2012/article/2012/01/21/eric-woerth-aurait-bien-brade-l-hippodrome-de-compiegne_1632853_1471069.html# eric-woerth-aurait-bien-brade-l-hippodrome-de-compiegne],''Le Monde'' (21 January 2012) {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Fillon I}}\n{{Fillon II}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woerth, Eric}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Creil]]\n[[Category:Panth\u00e9on-Assas University alumni]]\n[[Category:HEC Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Budget]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Civil Service]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Hauts-de-France]]\n[[Category:The Republicans (France) politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 12th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 13th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 14th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Expand French|topic=gov|date=February 2017}}\n{{ infobox Politician\n| name           = \u00c9ric Woerth\n| image          = \u00c9ric Woerth 2.jpg\n| office         = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br>for [[Oise's 4th constituency]]\n| term_start     = 17 June 2012\n| term_end       =\n| predecessor    = [[Christian Patria]]\n| office2        = [[Mayor (France)|Mayor]] of [[Chantilly, Oise|Chantilly]]\n| term_start2    = 1995\n| term_end2      = 2017\n| predecessor2   = Philippe Courboin\n| successor2     = Isabelle Wojtowiez\n| office3        = [[List of Budget Ministers of France|Minister of Budget]]\n| term_start3    = 2007\n| term_end3      = 2010\n| president3     = [[Nicolas Sarkozy]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]]\n| predecessor3   = [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Cop\u00e9]]\n| successor3     = [[Fran\u00e7ois Baroin]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1956|01|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Creil]], [[France]]\n| nationality    = [[France|French]]\n| party          = [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]]\n| alma_mater     = [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]], [[Sciences Po]], [[HEC Paris]]\n| spouse         = Florence Henry\n| children       = 2\n}}\n'''\u00c9ric Woerth''' (born 29 January 1956) is a French politician of [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] (LR).\n\n==Early life and education==\nWoerth was born in [[Creil]], [[Oise]]. He studied at [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]], [[HEC School of Management]] and [[Institut d'\u00c9tudes Politiques de Paris]]. \n\n==Political career==\n===Career in local politics===\n'''''Municipal Council'''''\n\nMayor of [[Chantilly, Oise]] : 1995-2004 (Resignation) / And since 2005. Reelected in 2001, 2005, 2008.\n\nDeputy-mayor of [[Chantilly, Oise]] : 2004-2005.\n\nMunicipal councillor of [[Chantilly, Oise]] : Since 1995. Reelected in 2001, 2008.\n\n'''''Community of communes Council'''''\n\nPresident of the [[Communaut\u00e9 de communes]] of the aire cantilenne{{typo help inline|reason=similar to cantilene|date=November 2019}} : Since 1995. Reelected in 2001, 2008.\n\nMember of the [[Communaut\u00e9 de communes]] of the aire cantilienne : Since 1995. Reelected in 2001, 2008.\n\nVice-president of the Regional Council of Picardy : 1992-1998.\n\nRegional councillor of [[Picardy]] : 1986-2002 (Resignation). Reelected in 1992, 1998.\n\n===Member of the National Assembly, 2002\u20132004===\nWoerth was elected [[National Assembly of France|''d\u00e9put\u00e9'']] for [[Oise]] in 2002. In parliament, he served on the Finance Committee from 2002 until 2004.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA2960 \u00c9ric Woerth] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref> \n\nIn addition to his parliamentary work, Woerth was the treasurer of the [[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] until he resigned in July 2010.<ref>[http://www.france-info.com/france-politique-2010-07-13-eric-woerth-va-bien-sur-quitter-son-poste-de-tresorier-de-l-ump-465443-9-10.html ''Eric Woerth va, \"bien s\u00fbr\", quitter son poste de tr\u00e9sorier de l\u2019UMP''] (Eric Worth will \u201cof course\u201d resign his post as treasurer of UMP)</ref>\n\n===Career in government===\nWoerth was state secretary for state reform in the government<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/may/13/france.worlddispatch|title=Commission impossible|last=Henley|first=Jon|date=2004-05-13|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=2017-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> of [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Jean-Pierre Raffarin]] from 2004 to 2005.\n\nWoerth founded the \"''club de la boussole''\", a group of UMP ''d\u00e9put\u00e9s'', and is a member of the ''[[R\u00e9formateurs]]'', a liberal trend within the UMP.\n\nWoerth was the Minister for the Budget, Public Accounts and the Civil Service from 2007 until 2010, in the government of [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]].<ref>[http://www.elysee.fr/elysee/elysee.fr/francais/interventions/2007/mai/composition_du_gouvernement.77059.html Communiqu\u00e9 de la Pr\u00e9sidence de la R\u00e9publique concernant la composition du gouvernement de M. Fran\u00e7ois FILLON, Premier ministre. ], ''[[\u00c9lys\u00e9e Palace]], 18 May 2007.</ref> In this capacity, he oversaw French authorities obtaining Swiss bank account data amid a push to catch tax cheats.<ref>David Jolly (August 30, 2009), [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/31/business/global/31iht-tax.html France Pursues Tax Cheats Using Swiss Banks] ''[[International Herald Tribune]]''.</ref>\n\nWoerth later served as [[Minister of Labour (France)|Minister of Labor, Solidarity and Civil Service]] from March until November 2010.<ref>http://www.foxbusiness.com/story/markets/frances-woerth-named-labor-minister-budget-minister/</ref>\n\n===Member of the National Assembly, 2010\u2013present===\nIn parliament, Woerth served on the Committee on Foreign Affairs from 2010 until 2012 before moving to the Finance Committee in 2012.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA2960 \u00c9ric Woerth] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref> In addition to his committee assignments, he has been a member of the [[Franco-German Parliamentary Assembly]] since 2019.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA2960 \u00c9ric Woerth] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref>\n\nIn the Republicans\u2019 [[2016 The Republicans (France) presidential primary|2016 presidential primaries]], Woerth endorsed [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]] as the party's candidate for the office of [[President of France]].<ref>[https://www.lopinion.fr/video/actu/eric-woerth-francois-fillon-sera-tres-grand-president-republique-115224 \u00c9ric Woerth : \u00abFran\u00e7ois Fillon sera un tr\u00e8s grand pr\u00e9sident de la R\u00e9publique\u00bb] ''[[L'Opinion]]'', November 25, 2016.</ref> In the Republicans\u2019 [[2017 The Republicans (France) leadership election|2017 leadership election]], he endorsed [[Laurent Wauquiez]].<ref>Ludovic Vigogne (October 11, 2017), [https://www.lopinion.fr/edition/politique/liste-136-parrains-laurent-wauquiez-135723 La liste des 136 parrains de Laurent Wauquiez] ''[[L'Opinion (French newspaper)|L'Opinion]]''.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Woerth was one of the few LR members who abstained from a vote on the French ratification of the [[European Union]]\u2019s [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement]] (CETA) with [[Canada]].<ref>Maxime Vaudano (24 July 2019), [https://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2019/07/24/ceta-qui-a-vote-quoi-parmi-les-deputes_5493039_4355770.html CETA : qui a vot\u00e9 quoi parmi les d\u00e9put\u00e9s] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref>\n\nTogether with [[Benjamin Dirx]], Woerth published a non-legally binding report in 2019 which garnered international attention for its recommendations on preventing [[Short (finance)|short-sellers]] and activists from unfairly destabilising French corporates. These included widening the disclosures of short positions to [[Derivative (finance)|derivatives instruments]], pushing for more transparency around the borrowing and lending of stock, and investigating whether market functions are jeopardised once short selling reaches a certain volume of shares.<ref>David Keohane and Harriet Agnew (October 2, 2019), [https://www.ft.com/content/1a8fbed2-e4fe-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59 France seeks crackdown on short sellers and activist investors] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref><ref>Laurence Boisseau (December 3, 2019), [https://www.lesechos.fr/finance-marches/marches-financiers/lactiviste-muddy-waters-defend-les-vertus-de-la-vente-a-decouvert-1153121 L'activiste Muddy Waters d\u00e9fend les vertus de la vente \u00e0 d\u00e9couvert] ''[[Les \u00c9chos]]''.</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nOn 5 July 2010, following its investigations on the ''Liliane Bettencourt and \u00c9ric Woerth'' political controversy, the online newspaper [[Mediapart]] revealed a report where Claire Thibout, an ex-accountant working for [[Liliane Bettencourt]], accused Nicolas Sarkozy and Woerth of receiving illegal campaign donations in 2007, in cash.<ref>[http://www.mediapart.fr/ ''L'ex-comptable des Bettencourt accuse: des enveloppes d'argent \u00e0 Woerth et \u00e0 Sarkozy''], original report, in French<!-- right now on the main page, no other URL --></ref><ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/e72598de-88d5-11df-8925-00144feab49a.html Financial Times]</ref> The ''[[Canard encha\u00een\u00e9]]'' and ''[[Marianne (magazine)|Marianne]]'' weeklies later revealed that Woerth authorized the sale of the [[Compiegne]] racetrack to a group with close connections to the [[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]], for a very low price and through an improper procedure.<ref>[http://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Actualite/Compiegne-Woerth-reste-en-selle-207418/ \u00ab Compi\u00e8gne : Woerth reste en selle \u00bb], ''[[Le Journal du dimanche]]'', 14 juillet 2010.</ref> He was placed under formal investigation by the [[Cour de Justice de la R\u00e9publique]] for that sale. All charges against him were dismissed in 2015.<ref>[[:fr:Affaire Woerth-Bettencourt#D\u00e9cision de renvois en correctionnelle et relaxe]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.blog-ewoerth.com/ \u00c9ric Woerth's blog] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2010/07/02/affaire-bettencourt-les-banques-suisses-chargent-eric-woerth_1381985_3224.html#ens_id=1373579&xtor=RSS-3208 Affaire Bettencourt : les banques suisses chargent Eric Woerth], ''Le Monde'' (2 July 2010) {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.liberation.fr/societe/01012302681-la-justice-rattrape-woerth-au-pas-de-course# la justice rattrape woerth au pas de course], ''Lib\u00e9ration'' (17 November 2010) {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2012/article/2012/01/21/eric-woerth-aurait-bien-brade-l-hippodrome-de-compiegne_1632853_1471069.html# eric-woerth-aurait-bien-brade-l-hippodrome-de-compiegne],''Le Monde'' (21 January 2012) {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Fillon I}}\n{{Fillon II}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woerth, Eric}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Creil]]\n[[Category:Panth\u00e9on-Assas University alumni]]\n[[Category:HEC Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Budget]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Civil Service]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Hauts-de-France]]\n[[Category:The Republicans (France) politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 12th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 13th National Asse